Aero_Fit CaseStudy My intent and motivation to solve this case study is to become more skilled, aware, and creative in the way I observe the data. I would like to take this opportunity to infer as many understanding from the data as possible. This casestudy is of a company who designs the treadmills with 3 models and the types of users who use them and their details. There are 3 segments- 1- Entry level KP281 costing $1500 2- Mid level KP481 costing $1750 3- High level KP781 costing $2500 I have first tried to understand the data for its description and cleanliness to determine what type of cleaning is needed whether needed or not. According to the first operation on data it seems that there are in total 9 variables out of which, 3 are categorical and 6 are numerical 3 categorical vairables are- 1- Product type 2- Gender 3- Marital Status 6 Numerical variables are- 1- Age 2- Education 3- Usage (hours) 4- Fitness (1-5) 5- Income 6- Miles (ridden on the treadmill) There are in total 180 entries There are no NaN values in the data The diversity of the products are as follows- KP281 Entry level- 80 units KP481 Mid level- 60 units KP781 High level- 40 units There are in total 104 Males and 76 Females The marital status of them are 107 Partnered and 73 Single

def clip_data(df_entry):
    df_clipped_entry = df_entry.copy()
    for col in df.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']):
        q5 = df_clipped_entry[col].quantile(0.05)
        q95 = df_clipped_entry[col].quantile(0.95)
        df_clipped_entry[col] = df_clipped_entry[col].clip(lower=q5, upper=q95)
    return df_clipped_entry
    
df_clipped_entry = clip_data(df_entry.copy())
df_clipped_mid = clip_data(df_mid.copy())
df_clipped_adv = clip_data(df_adv.copy())
df_clipped = clip_data(df.copy())

#Checking the Marginal Probability of Gender wrt Product choice
Gender_Product_CT = pd.crosstab(df_clipped['Gender'], df_clipped['Product'])

marg_prob_Gender = Gender_Product_CT.div(Gender_Product_CT.sum(1), axis=0) 
marg_prob_Product = Gender_Product_CT.div(Gender_Product_CT.sum(0), axis=1)

print(marg_prob_Gender)
print(marg_prob_Product)

In the Mid-level product segment, the probability of a male purchasing the product is slightly more than the female at 51.7% to 48.3%.
In the advanced level product KP781 we can notice the product segment being dominated by males there is an 82% chance that a male
will purchase an advanced level product but only 17% chance that a female will purchase the product.'''
